			    STPJS 256</div>
  <p class="cont">keeping all the commandments of God.<span class="footRef">1</span> But we cannot keep all the commandments without first
  knowing them,<span class="footRef">2</span> and we cannot expect to know all, or more than we now know unless we comply<span class="footRef">3</span>
  with or keep those we have already received. That which is wrong under one circumstance, may be,
  and often is, right under another.</p>
  <p class="std">God said, &ldquo;Thou shalt not kill;&rdquo;<span class="footRef">4</span> at another time He said, &ldquo;Thou shalt utterly destroy.&rdquo;<span class="footRef">5</span> This is
  the principle on which the government of heaven is conducted&mdash;by revelation adapted to the
  circumstances in which the children of the kingdom<span class="footRef">6</span> are placed. Whatever God requires is right,<span class="footRef">7</span>
  no matter what it is, although we may not see the reason<span class="footRef">8</span> thereof till long after the events transpire.
  If we seek first the kingdom of God, all good things will be added.<span class="footRef">9</span> So with Solomon: first he asked
  wisdom,<span class="footRef">10</span> and God gave it him, and with it every desire of his heart,<span class="footRef">11</span> even things which might be
  considered abominable<span class="footRef">12</span> to all who understand the order of heaven<span class="footRef">13</span> only in part,<span class="footRef">14</span> but which in
  reality were right because God gave and sanctioned by special revelation.<span class="footRef">15</span></p>
  <p class="std">A parent may whip a child,<span class="footRef">16</span> and justly, too, because he stole an apple; whereas if the child had
  asked for the apple, and the parent had given it, the child would have eaten it with a better appetite;
  there would have been no stripes; all the pleasure of the apple would have been secured, all the
  misery of stealing lost.</p>
  <div class="topic">Every Gift from God Is Just</div>
  <p class="std">This principle will justly apply to all of God&rsquo;s dealings with His children. Everything that God
  gives us is lawful and right; and it is proper that we should enjoy His gifts and blessings whenever
  and wherever He is disposed to bestow; but if we should seize upon those same blessings<span class="footRef">17</span> and
  enjoyments without law, without revelation, without commandment, those blessings and enjoyments
  would prove cursings and vexations<span class="footRef">18</span> in the end, and we should have to lie down in sorrow<span class="footRef">19</span> and
  wailings of everlasting regret. But in obedience there is joy<span class="footRef">20</span> and peace unspotted, unalloyed; and
  as God has designed our happiness<span class="footRef">21</span>&mdash;and the happiness of all His creatures,<span class="footRef">22</span> he never has&mdash;He
  never will institute an ordinance<span class="footRef">23</span> or give a commandment to His people that is not calculated in its
  nature to promote that happiness which He has designed, and which will not end</p>
